        <h2>Guide to building a personal computer</h2>
        <br>
        <h3>Budget and purpose of a personal computer </h3>
        <p>The modern times we live in offer us a wide range of components. Whether you're a gaming enthusiast or work in the office, there are a variety of possibilities to choose from.</p>
        <p>If you want to build a personal computer yourself, you need to have a budget and a purpose for that computer in mind.</p>
        <p>If you are passionate about games or if you use demanding software but have a tight budget, you need to choose your components as balanced as possible.</p>
        <p>For example, if you choose to invest in a higher performance video card, but only have money left over for a weaker processor and less RAM, you risk the <b>Bottleneck</b> phenomenon.</p>
        <p>For the office sector, things are not quite the same. It is recommended to opt for a fast processor (Intel I3 10100, AMD Ryzen 3 3200G) with an integrated video card.</p>
        <p>Also, the motherboard and RAM must be taken into account.</p>
        <br>
        <!--Photo Galery-->
            <img src="/img/guide_pht1.png" class="pht">

        <p><b>*Notw: Bottleneck</b> = the phenomenon in which the whole system is slowed down because of the difference in performance between two or more components.</p>
        <br>
                    <!--Procesor-->
        <h3>Choosing the microprocessor</h3>
        <p>Currently, there are two giants when it comes to the production and marketing of microprocessors, <b>Intel</b> and <b>AMD</b>.</p>
        <p>The choice between these two companies has become preferential over time, with performance between the newer generations becoming similar.</p>
        <p>However, there are some differences, as the two processors only work on one type of motherboard socket.</p>
        <p><b>Intel</b> only works on LGA socket depending on generation:</p>
        <p>LGA 775(Pentium, Celeron, Core 2), LGA 1366(I7 900 Series), LGA 1155(2nd and 3rd generation), LGA 1150(4th generation), LGA1 1151(6th and 7th generation), </p>
        <p>LGA 1151 v2(8th and 9th generation) LGA 1200(10th, 11th generation) si LGA 1700(12th generation).</p>
        <p>Instead, <b>AMD</b> runs on its own PGA sockets:</p>
        <p>PGA AM2(Athlon 64, 64X), PGA AM2+(Athlon 64, Athlon X2, Phenom, Phenom II), PGA AMD3(Phenom II, Athlon II, Sempron, Opteron), PGA AM3+(AMD FX, Phenom II, AThlon II, Sempron),</p>
        <p> PGA AM4(Athlon 200, Ryzen 3, Ryzen 5, Ryzen 7, Ryzen 9). </p>
         <!--Photo Galery-->
         <img src="/img/guide_pht2.jpg" class="pht">
         <br>
         <p><b>*Note: Socket</b> = the slot on the motherboard where the microprocessor is inserted. The number next to it represents the number of pins of the microprocessor (e.g. Socket 1150 - 1150 pins).</p>
         <br>
                    <!--Placa de baza-->
         <h3>Choosing the motherboard</h3>
         <p>Like processors, there are a variety of motherboard models, each with more spectacular technologies</p>  
         <p>On the market, there are several motherboard manufacturers, such as Asus, Gigabyte, ASRock, MSI, Biostar and many others.</p>
         <p>To choose the perfect motherboard we have to take into account the processor generation (different sockets), speed and RAM technology (133Mhz, 1600Mhz, 3200Mhz, respectively DDR2, DDR3, DDR4),</p>
         <p>but also its sizes: Mini-ITX, Micro-ITX (the most used), ATX and EATX (Extenden ATX), to fit in the case slots.</p>
 
            <!--Photo Galery-->
         <img src="/img/guide_pht3.jpg" class="pht">
         <br>
                    <!--PLaca video-->
         <h3>Choosing the video card</h3>
         <p>In the case of video cards, there are 2 major manufacturers on the market: <b>Nvidia and AMD.</b></p>
         <p>As with microprocessors, the choice of one of these two companies became a matter of consumer preference.</p>
         <p>However, each company stands out for its own characteristics:</p>
         <p>Nvidia produces powerful models (RTX 3060, RTX 2070, GTX 1080, GTX 1660 TI) with proprietary technologies (Nvidia 3D Vision, DLSS, RTX) that run at low temperatures, but at a higher price than AMD's models.</p>
         <p>Similarly, AMD produces powerful models (RX 6800 XT, RX 5700XT, RX 5500XT, RX 570) with proprietary technologies (AMD Rqdeon ANti-Lag, AMD Freesync, AMD Smart Access Memory) that run at higher temperatures than Nvidia.</p>
         <p>An important factor of video cards is their memory, which can range from 1Gb to 24Gb.</p>
         <p>Similar to ram memory, they are developed with GDDR technology (GDDR3, GDDR5, GDDR6).</p>
         <p>All video cards, regardless of their age, have outputs for connection to a monitor/video projector. Most models now have DVI/HDMI/DisplayPort ports (the latest).</p>
        <!--Photo Galery-->
        <img src="/img/guide_pht4.png" class="pht">
        <br>
                    <!--Memoria RAM-->
        <h3>Choosing RAM memory</h3>
        <p>With the evolution of technology, RAM has become faster and more affordable.</p>
        <p>Memory RAM manufacturers on the market include Kingston, Corsair, Crucial, Pretec, Samsung, Viking.</p>
        <p>The compatibility with the motherboard (DDRx technology, but also its capacity) should be taken into account when choosing the appropriate RAM memory.
        <p>and with the microprocessor (frequency at which it runs, e.g. 2666Mhz).</p>
        <p>Too often an important factor that makes the difference between RAM memories is the latency representative. The lower the latency, the faster the RAM memory.</p>
        <p>RAM can run on the motherboard in: Single Channel (only one RAM card inserted on the motherboard - not recommended),</p>
        <p>in Dual Channel (two RAM cards that must run at the same frequency and latency - most recommended),</p>
        <p>in Quad Channel (four RAM cards that must run at the same frequency and latency - motherboard must be equipped with 4 RAM slots), but also mixed</p>
        <p>in groups of 3 cards (not recommended and unnecessary, losing a lot of performance).</p>
            <!--Photo Galery-->
            <img src="/img/guide_pht5.jpg" class="pht">
            <br>
            <p><b>*Notw: Latency</b> = the number of cycles/second RAM can process when it has something to do.</p>
            <p><b>*Note: Frequency</b> = RAM processing speed per second measured in MHz.</p>
            <br>
                    <!--Stoacrea: HDD/SSD/NVMe-->
            <h3>Storage</h3>
            <p>30, 40 years ago data storage was a big problem for the computer world, it was always too little, too slow and too expensive.</p> 
            <p>Nowadays we can say that we are living in lucky times, because the process of storage evolution is a long one</p>
            <p>From a capacity of just a few Kb and low speeds, storage devices have reached fabulous capacities of a few Tb and speeds of up to 32 Gb/s</p>
            <p>There are now plenty of storage device manufacturers on the market, such as Samsung, Western Digital, Seagate, Kingston, Crucial, Intel, Adata.</p>
            <p>The storage devices include: HDD (Hard Disk Device - can reach speeds up to 200 Mb/s), SSD (Solid State Driver - can reach speeds up to 6 Gb/s).</p>
            <p>and NVMe SSD(nonvolatile memory express - can reach speeds up to 32 Gb/s).</p>
            <p>HDDs and SSDs are connected to the motherboard via a SATA (Serial ATA) cable, while the NVMe SSD is attached directly to the motherboard via an M2-type socket.</p>
            <p>Recommended, for building a personal computer, is to mount a HDD (500Gb+ for applications and games) and a SATA or NVMe SSD (256Gb+ for operating system and applications that require higher operating speed).</p>
